The common ratio of a geometric series is found by dividing any term by the previous term.
In this case, the common ratio is $\frac{-5/3}{-3/5}=\boxed{\frac{25}{9}}$.
The answer is: \frac{25}{9}

The inverse of a $2 \times 2$ matrix $\begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{pmatrix}$ is given by
\[\frac{1}{ad - bc} \begin{pmatrix} d & -b \\ -c & a \end{pmatrix}.\]In this case, $ad - bc = (9)(-12) - (18)(-6) = 0,$ so the inverse does not exist.
Therefore, the inverse is the zero matrix $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix}}.$The answer is: \begin{pmatrix}0&0\0&0\end{pmatrix}

The absolute value of a complex number $a+bi$ is given by $\sqrt{a^2+b^2}$.
So, the absolute value of $\frac{5}{6}+2i$ is $\sqrt{\left(\frac{5}{6}\right)^2+(2)^2}=\sqrt{\frac{25}{36}+4}=\sqrt{\frac{25+144}{36}}=\sqrt{\frac{169}{36}}=\frac{13}{6}$.
Therefore, $\left|\frac{5}{6}+2i\right|=\boxed{\frac{13}{6}}$. The answer is: \frac{13}{6}

